		By: Srinivas		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.com/exercise-and-depression#comment-985</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Srinivas]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Wed, 08 May 2013 20:41:17 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=5008#comment-985</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[James,

Prior to becoming an avid surfer I used to have a really bad case of IBS. I tried just about everything from diet changes to anti-depressants. What&#039;s interesting is I was also fairly depressed during most of that time. Everything really stressed me about. Something as a simple as a long line would send me into a frenzy. 

When I started surfing all that changed.  The stomach aches really calmed down. I felt emotionally and physically better than I ever have. SO it&#039;s not surprise to me that exercise has the impact on depression that it does.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>James,</p>
<p>Prior to becoming an avid surfer I used to have a really bad case of IBS. I tried just about everything from diet changes to anti-depressants. What&#8217;s interesting is I was also fairly depressed during most of that time. Everything really stressed me about. Something as a simple as a long line would send me into a frenzy. </p>
<p>When I started surfing all that changed.  The stomach aches really calmed down. I felt emotionally and physically better than I ever have. SO it&#8217;s not surprise to me that exercise has the impact on depression that it does.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
